1
00:00:09,607 --> 00:00:11,165
Hello, Roz.

2
00:00:11,327 --> 00:00:12,555
I say, hello, Roz.

3
00:00:12,727 --> 00:00:14,240
Oh, I'm sorry.

4
00:00:14,407 --> 00:00:16,762
Oh, don't be.
I didn't mean to disturb your reading.

5
00:00:16,927 --> 00:00:18,838
- Actually, I'm doing a little research.
- Mm-hm.

6
00:00:19,007 --> 00:00:20,838
Um, I have a meeting
with a publisher tomorrow.

7
00:00:21,007 --> 00:00:22,440
I'm thinking of writing
a children's book.

8
00:00:22,607 --> 00:00:23,596
- Really?
- Yeah.

9
00:00:23,767 --> 00:00:25,758
It's a story my mom made up for me
when I was a kid.

10
00:00:25,927 --> 00:00:27,360
I tell it to Alice all the time now.

11
00:00:27,527 --> 00:00:29,597
I thought it'd be a kick
if I could get it published.

12
00:00:29,767 --> 00:00:32,804
Good for you, Roz. You know,
I've dabbled in juvenile fiction myself.

13
00:00:33,167 --> 00:00:35,123
Yes, Niles and I,
when we were boys,

14
00:00:35,287 --> 00:00:37,960
wrote a series of stories together
in which we were the heroes.

15
00:00:38,127 --> 00:00:41,597
Along the lines of <i>The Hardy Boys</i>
or a <i>Nancy Drew.</i>

16
00:00:41,767 --> 00:00:43,758
<i>The Nancy Boys?</i>

17
00:00:46,247 --> 00:00:47,965
No.

18
00:00:48,687 --> 00:00:50,723
Called <i>The Crane Boys Mysteries.</i>

19
00:00:50,887 --> 00:00:54,675
They were two plucky lads who used
their keen psychological insight

20
00:00:54,847 --> 00:00:57,998
to solve crimes brought home
by their detective father.

21
00:00:58,167 --> 00:01:01,079
- How many of these did you write?
- Thirty-four.

22
00:01:01,247 --> 00:01:04,956
Yes, there was "The Mystery
of the One-Eared Monkey,"

23
00:01:05,127 --> 00:01:07,482
"On Your Mark, Get Set, Die,"

24
00:01:07,647 --> 00:01:10,286
and there was one
where our father was kidnapped

25
00:01:10,447 --> 00:01:14,042
and the only clue
was a dented Ballantine can.

26
00:01:14,207 --> 00:01:16,357
- "The Suspicious Six-Pack."
- Excellent.

27
00:01:16,527 --> 00:01:18,597
- Please, Niles, pull up a chair.
- All right, I will.

28
00:01:18,767 --> 00:01:20,723
I can't stay long though.
Uh, latte to go, please.

29
00:01:20,887 --> 00:01:22,843
I'm on my way to the spa
to pick up Daphne.

30
00:01:23,007 --> 00:01:25,680
Oh, that reminds me, what time
should I be at the apartment tonight?

31
00:01:25,847 --> 00:01:28,725
Oh, well, let's see.
It's an hour's trip to the spa

32
00:01:28,887 --> 00:01:30,605
and there's a two-hour
graduation ceremony,

33
00:01:30,767 --> 00:01:34,237
at the end of which they all throw
their fat pants into the air.

34
00:01:34,727 --> 00:01:36,683
- Say 7:00.
- Okay, great. I'll see you there.

35
00:01:36,847 --> 00:01:37,962
NILES: Yes.
- Bye. Bye, Roz.

36
00:01:38,127 --> 00:01:39,924
- Now, speaking of Daphne, ahem,
- Mm-hm.

37
00:01:40,087 --> 00:01:41,679
I was hoping
you could spare her Friday.

38
00:01:41,847 --> 00:01:43,917
I'm planning to take her
on a little getaway weekend,

39
00:01:44,087 --> 00:01:48,558
where I think we may be taking
our relationship to the next level.

40
00:01:48,727 --> 00:01:50,718
Oh, my God, Niles,
you're going to propose?

41
00:01:50,887 --> 00:01:53,117
No, not that level.
The level before that.

42
00:01:54,087 --> 00:01:55,679
You're gonna ask her
to move in with you?

43
00:01:55,847 --> 00:01:57,678
One more level before that.

44
00:01:58,247 --> 00:02:00,636
- Well, you're already dating.
- No, that's two levels.

45
00:02:00,807 --> 00:02:02,877
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

46
00:02:03,047 --> 00:02:05,003
Oh, for heaven's sake, just tell me.

47
00:02:05,167 --> 00:02:10,366
Well, you know, we're going
to consummate our relationship.

48
00:02:11,927 --> 00:02:13,485
What?

49
00:02:15,007 --> 00:02:18,556
Well, uh... Gosh, l...
It's none of my business.

50
00:02:18,727 --> 00:02:21,480
I just thought you'd already
reached that level.

51
00:02:21,647 --> 00:02:22,966
What made you think that?

52
00:02:23,127 --> 00:02:25,038
Ooh, I don't know.
I guess everybody just assumed.

53
00:02:25,207 --> 00:02:27,038
- Who's everybody?
- Nobody.

54
00:02:28,847 --> 00:02:32,556
But, Niles, you have been on
overnight trips together, haven't you?

55
00:02:32,727 --> 00:02:34,399
Well, yes,
but they were perfectly chaste.

56
00:02:34,567 --> 00:02:35,636
Oh.

57
00:02:35,807 --> 00:02:37,957
Daphne wanted to wait
until the time was right.

58
00:02:38,127 --> 00:02:40,402
And, well, we've just both
been missing each other so much

59
00:02:40,567 --> 00:02:44,321
these last few weeks,
I think the time is upon us.

60
00:02:44,487 --> 00:02:46,876
- Oh, I'm happy for you, Niles.
- Thank you.

61
00:02:47,047 --> 00:02:50,835
Gosh, nobody's gonna believe
you two haven't slept together.

62
00:02:51,007 --> 00:02:53,441
- Who's nobody?
- Nobody.

63
00:03:02,607 --> 00:03:04,916
- I love you, Niles.
- I love you too.

64
00:03:05,087 --> 00:03:06,315
Oh, hey, I got you something.

65
00:03:07,367 --> 00:03:08,766
Here.

66
00:03:10,607 --> 00:03:13,758
Oh, Niles, it's lovely.

67
00:03:14,167 --> 00:03:15,885
But I already
have a dress like this.

68
00:03:16,047 --> 00:03:17,116
I know. That's it.

69
00:03:17,287 --> 00:03:20,245
That's the dress you wore five years
ago when we danced the tango.

70
00:03:21,247 --> 00:03:22,600
I don't understand.

71
00:03:23,207 --> 00:03:24,481
It's for this weekend.

72
00:03:25,327 --> 00:03:26,521
Only this time,

73
00:03:26,687 --> 00:03:32,159
instead of ending in heartache,
the evening can end in triumph.

74
00:03:32,847 --> 00:03:36,522
That's very romantic,
but I'm not sure I can fit into it.

75
00:03:36,687 --> 00:03:37,802
Not yet anyway.

76
00:03:37,967 --> 00:03:40,037
Oh, nonsense.
You're as svelte as you ever were.

77
00:03:40,207 --> 00:03:41,435
You're sweet.

78
00:03:41,607 --> 00:03:43,120
It was cute
when I came out of the spa

79
00:03:43,287 --> 00:03:45,005
and you pretended
you couldn't see me.

80
00:03:45,167 --> 00:03:46,486
Who said that? Who's in my car?

81
00:03:46,647 --> 00:03:48,922
[DAPHNE LAUGHING]

82
00:03:49,127 --> 00:03:51,721
Well, you've worked so hard
and you stuck with it.

83
00:03:51,887 --> 00:03:53,605
I want you to know
how proud I am.

84
00:03:53,767 --> 00:03:55,644
Actually, I'm proud of myself.

85
00:03:55,807 --> 00:03:58,924
The staff therapist even
complimented me on my willpower.

86
00:03:59,087 --> 00:04:00,486
Oh, so you did see a therapist?

87
00:04:00,647 --> 00:04:02,046
Yeah, it's all part
of the programme

88
00:04:02,207 --> 00:04:04,243
to help you figure out
the cause of your overeating.

89
00:04:04,407 --> 00:04:07,763
Mm-hm. Well, if you ask me,
it's a classic case of sublimation,

90
00:04:07,927 --> 00:04:10,043
using food as a substitute for sex.

91
00:04:10,567 --> 00:04:12,717
I recommend
you see a certain doctor

92
00:04:12,887 --> 00:04:14,878
I know very well,
he can help you.

93
00:04:15,047 --> 00:04:17,163
Yeah. That's not what Gloria thinks.

94
00:04:17,327 --> 00:04:20,239
- Heh. Gloria?
- The therapist.

95
00:04:20,407 --> 00:04:21,396
Oh.

96
00:04:21,567 --> 00:04:25,037
My patients call me Dr. Crane,
but, uh, whatever.

97
00:04:25,207 --> 00:04:27,926
So, uh, what does Gloria think?

98
00:04:28,087 --> 00:04:29,918
She thinks
I may have gained the weight

99
00:04:30,087 --> 00:04:32,362
as a way to create distance
between us.

100
00:04:32,527 --> 00:04:33,960
Oh. Hmm...

101
00:04:34,127 --> 00:04:36,243
And, uh, why
would you wanna do that?

102
00:04:36,607 --> 00:04:39,360
Well, when you and I
first came together,

103
00:04:39,527 --> 00:04:41,518
we decided to wait
and get to know each other

104
00:04:41,687 --> 00:04:44,155
before bringing the relationship
into the bedroom.

105
00:04:44,527 --> 00:04:47,041
Then as time went on,
you told me all these stories

106
00:04:47,207 --> 00:04:49,277
about how you'd pined for me
for seven years,

107
00:04:49,447 --> 00:04:52,041
how I'd been
your unobtainable dream.

108
00:04:52,207 --> 00:04:54,243
How could anybody
live up to that?

109
00:04:55,127 --> 00:04:57,721
See, Gloria thinks I was terrified
of letting you down,

110
00:04:57,887 --> 00:05:00,765
of not being perfect, so I ate.

111
00:05:01,287 --> 00:05:04,085
And I ate. And apparently ate.

112
00:05:04,247 --> 00:05:05,646
[DAPHNE LAUGHING]

113
00:05:05,807 --> 00:05:08,321
Daphne,
you couldn't possibly let me down.

114
00:05:09,327 --> 00:05:11,443
And as for the weight,
it didn't matter.

115
00:05:11,607 --> 00:05:12,801
I never noticed.

116
00:05:13,327 --> 00:05:16,603
That's another thing.
I gained 60 pounds.

117
00:05:16,767 --> 00:05:18,803
Don't you think it's strange
you couldn't see it?

118
00:05:18,967 --> 00:05:21,356
No, it's not strange. I love you.

119
00:05:21,727 --> 00:05:23,718
And I love you too.

120
00:05:25,927 --> 00:05:27,440
You know what Gloria says?

121
00:05:29,007 --> 00:05:30,440
No.

122
00:05:30,607 --> 00:05:32,404
She says
you couldn't see the extra weight

123
00:05:32,567 --> 00:05:34,478
because you're only seeing
the perfect me

124
00:05:34,647 --> 00:05:36,842
you've carried around
in your head for seven years.

125
00:05:37,007 --> 00:05:39,680
She calls it
"looking through love goggles."

126
00:05:40,687 --> 00:05:42,518
Alrighty, let's get her on the phone,
shall we?

127
00:05:42,687 --> 00:05:44,882
Niles, don't.
I'm not trying to upset you.

128
00:05:45,047 --> 00:05:47,641
I'm just telling you
what we discussed in therapy.

129
00:05:47,807 --> 00:05:49,798
I understand, I understand.

130
00:05:49,967 --> 00:05:53,084
And I know how much
you've looked forward to this weekend,

131
00:05:53,247 --> 00:05:57,160
but until I sort this out, I may need
a little more time before I'm...

132
00:05:57,327 --> 00:05:58,316
Absolutely. Say no more.

133
00:05:58,487 --> 00:06:01,081
We can easily postpone
the weekend.

134
00:06:02,607 --> 00:06:05,917
Of course, if my theory is correct and
you are eating as a substitute for sex,

135
00:06:06,087 --> 00:06:07,486
then you're taking a terrible risk.

136
00:06:07,647 --> 00:06:09,046
[NILES IMITATES EXPLOSION
AND DAPHNE LAUGHS]

137
00:06:09,207 --> 00:06:11,675
I know, huh?

138
00:06:13,887 --> 00:06:15,923
I love you, Niles.

139
00:06:16,407 --> 00:06:18,443
I love you too.

140
00:06:20,687 --> 00:06:22,803
[FOOTSTEPS]

141
00:06:22,967 --> 00:06:25,435
MARTIN: Roz, you know,
if you really wanna do a kid's book,

142
00:06:25,607 --> 00:06:27,006
you ought to write one
about Eddie.

143
00:06:27,167 --> 00:06:30,204
- I'd buy one about Eddie.
- Thanks, but I already have an idea.

144
00:06:30,367 --> 00:06:33,279
Besides, if I was gonna use a dog,
I'd probably use my own.

145
00:06:33,447 --> 00:06:36,166
Well, you wanna make your dog happy
or you wanna sell books?

146
00:06:36,327 --> 00:06:38,887
Now, I was thinking,
Eddie joins the circus.

147
00:06:39,047 --> 00:06:41,436
And he has all this clown makeup on
and everything, you know.

148
00:06:41,607 --> 00:06:42,676
And he juggles and stuff.

149
00:06:42,847 --> 00:06:45,236
And then you could do one
where he invents this flying machine

150
00:06:45,407 --> 00:06:47,682
and has all these wacky adventures.

151
00:06:47,847 --> 00:06:49,246
That's kind of cute.

152
00:06:49,407 --> 00:06:51,125
He could join a flock of geese

153
00:06:51,287 --> 00:06:55,439
or he could become
the world's first dog traffic reporter.

154
00:06:55,887 --> 00:06:58,003
Eddie would never do that.

155
00:06:58,167 --> 00:07:00,886
You really don't get Eddie, do you?

156
00:07:01,047 --> 00:07:02,036
[DOOR OPENS]

157
00:07:02,487 --> 00:07:04,876
- Hey, look who's home.
MARTIN: Hey.

158
00:07:05,287 --> 00:07:08,245
- Is this all for me?
- Oh, Daphne. God, we missed you.

159
00:07:08,407 --> 00:07:10,363
- You look great, Daphne.
- Thank you, Roz.

160
00:07:10,527 --> 00:07:11,926
MARTIN:
Great? You look fantastic.

161
00:07:12,087 --> 00:07:14,885
I don't know what they did to you there,
but what a difference.

162
00:07:15,047 --> 00:07:16,958
Yes, I was getting pretty big,
wasn't I?

163
00:07:17,127 --> 00:07:19,243
Big? You were ginormous.

164
00:07:19,407 --> 00:07:20,760
FRASIER:
Dad.

165
00:07:20,927 --> 00:07:22,838
- I'm telling her how good she looks.
- Yes, yes.

166
00:07:23,007 --> 00:07:25,362
- Come here, old man.
- You really do look lovely, Daphne.

167
00:07:25,527 --> 00:07:29,076
Oh, thank you, Dr. Crane.
But I still have to be careful what I eat.

168
00:07:29,247 --> 00:07:30,600
Yes, of course. And to that end,

169
00:07:30,767 --> 00:07:32,997
I have a little surprise for you
in the refrigerator.

170
00:07:33,167 --> 00:07:34,725
You didn't have to do that.

171
00:07:34,887 --> 00:07:36,639
It's not some of those
low-cal dinners, is it?

172
00:07:36,807 --> 00:07:37,922
FRASIER:
Just go look.

173
00:07:38,087 --> 00:07:39,076
[LAUGHS]

174
00:07:39,247 --> 00:07:41,363
[SQUEALING]

175
00:07:43,767 --> 00:07:45,564
That's hysterical.

176
00:07:45,727 --> 00:07:48,082
It's called the Refrigerator Pig.
It's a little plastic pig.

177
00:07:48,247 --> 00:07:49,600
He's got a recording in his belly.

178
00:07:49,767 --> 00:07:51,359
Every time you open
the refrigerator door,

179
00:07:51,527 --> 00:07:53,006
you'll hear his scolding squeal.

180
00:07:53,807 --> 00:07:55,525
So, Daphne,
tell us about the spa.

181
00:07:55,687 --> 00:07:57,359
Well, it was lots of hard work.

182
00:07:57,527 --> 00:08:00,837
We had hikes every morning
and sessions with a personal trainer.

183
00:08:01,007 --> 00:08:04,124
And a wonderful therapist.
You're gonna love this.

184
00:08:06,527 --> 00:08:08,802
Yes, there was a professional
therapist on staff.

185
00:08:08,967 --> 00:08:11,117
Mm-hm. Named Gloria.

186
00:08:11,287 --> 00:08:13,278
Who helped me dig down
to the root of my problems.

187
00:08:13,447 --> 00:08:15,358
Yes, Gloria's very handy
with a shovel.

188
00:08:15,527 --> 00:08:16,516
[LAUGHS]

189
00:08:17,207 --> 00:08:19,880
Well, she must have been very good.
I mean, obviously, look at you.

190
00:08:20,047 --> 00:08:23,357
Well, Gloria's very empathetic because
she had a similar weight problem.

191
00:08:23,527 --> 00:08:25,438
Only she didn't have anyone
to help deal with it.

192
00:08:25,607 --> 00:08:27,245
She had to battle it alone for years.

193
00:08:27,407 --> 00:08:29,443
She didn't have a boyfriend
she could blame?

194
00:08:30,847 --> 00:08:32,803
Is there something
you want to say to me?

195
00:08:33,087 --> 00:08:34,361
No.

196
00:08:34,527 --> 00:08:38,406
Well, I've got something to say.
I would like to propose a toast.

197
00:08:38,567 --> 00:08:40,637
I was very lucky
to have someone like Gloria.

198
00:08:40,807 --> 00:08:44,766
Yes. You usually have to go all the way
to a hair salon for that kind of insight.

199
00:08:45,727 --> 00:08:47,683
NILES: Here, I'll take that.
FRASIER: Yes, uh...

200
00:08:47,847 --> 00:08:51,965
Well, uh, Daphne, the important thing
is that you're feeling better

201
00:08:52,127 --> 00:08:54,277
and that you're back home
where you belong.

202
00:08:54,447 --> 00:08:56,756
MARTIN: Right.
- I better make mine water.

203
00:08:56,927 --> 00:08:59,236
Champagne is pure sugar,
you know.

204
00:09:00,607 --> 00:09:02,120
Niles, what the hell
is wrong with you?

205
00:09:02,287 --> 00:09:05,359
Oh, Frasier, you would not believe
the hack psychobabble

206
00:09:05,527 --> 00:09:07,279
this woman
has filled Daphne's head with.

207
00:09:07,447 --> 00:09:09,915
Well, even if that's true,
that's no reason to act like an ass.

208
00:09:10,087 --> 00:09:12,885
Now, you just shape up
and treat Daphne with respect.

209
00:09:13,047 --> 00:09:14,639
[SQUEALING]

210
00:09:19,287 --> 00:09:20,276
DAPHNE:
Ooh...

211
00:09:20,847 --> 00:09:24,681
Apparently that pig of yours
can dish it out, but he can't take it.

212
00:09:26,407 --> 00:09:28,875
- So how about that toast?
- Oh, good idea.

213
00:09:29,047 --> 00:09:30,196
FRASIER:
Right, uh...

214
00:09:30,367 --> 00:09:31,686
To Daphne.

215
00:09:31,847 --> 00:09:36,762
Your warmth and spirit
have helped make this place a home.

216
00:09:36,927 --> 00:09:40,966
Your influence can be seen
in a thousand different ways.

217
00:09:41,127 --> 00:09:43,197
Unless, of course,
one's wearing his love goggles.

218
00:09:43,367 --> 00:09:45,801
That's it.
Niles, I think you should go.

219
00:09:46,327 --> 00:09:49,364
- What?
- I want you to leave right now.

220
00:10:11,247 --> 00:10:14,478
Nice call on the Refrigerator Pig.

221
00:10:21,447 --> 00:10:23,085
So you don't think
I have a germ phobia?

222
00:10:23,247 --> 00:10:26,603
Not at all. Just a healthy sense
of personal hygiene.

223
00:10:26,767 --> 00:10:30,157
Ah. Here is the number of the man
who cleans my telephones.

224
00:10:30,327 --> 00:10:33,444
There you go. The best in Seattle.
Now, you take care.

225
00:10:33,607 --> 00:10:36,360
No, don't touch, don't touch.
There you go.

226
00:10:37,047 --> 00:10:40,596
Frasier.
Uh, what are you doing here?

227
00:10:40,767 --> 00:10:44,680
Oh, I just wanted to see
how you were doing after last night.

228
00:10:44,847 --> 00:10:46,724
Daphne caught me up
on what's been going on.

229
00:10:46,887 --> 00:10:50,880
Oh, wonderful. So she's talking to
every therapist under the sun but me.

230
00:10:51,207 --> 00:10:52,959
She said she tried to talk to you.

231
00:10:53,127 --> 00:10:55,482
No, she tried to blame me.

232
00:10:55,647 --> 00:10:58,445
According to
her puppet master, Gloria,

233
00:10:58,607 --> 00:11:00,359
Daphne overate
because she was afraid

234
00:11:00,527 --> 00:11:03,644
she couldn't live up
to my image of her.

235
00:11:04,127 --> 00:11:07,085
- Well, there may be something to that.
- Oh...

236
00:11:07,287 --> 00:11:11,997
She does have seven years
of fantasy to live up to.

237
00:11:12,167 --> 00:11:13,680
What fantasy?

238
00:11:13,847 --> 00:11:15,883
I have a very realistic picture
of Daphne.

239
00:11:16,047 --> 00:11:19,323
I love her for who she is.
I have since the very beginning.

240
00:11:19,487 --> 00:11:22,684
All right, when exactly was the very
beginning for the two of you anyway?

241
00:11:22,847 --> 00:11:26,726
Well, don't you remember?
You introduced us.

242
00:11:26,887 --> 00:11:29,720
Daphne, this is my brother, Niles.

243
00:11:31,247 --> 00:11:33,761
- You're Daphne?
- Why, yes, I am.

244
00:11:34,087 --> 00:11:37,079
Well, when Frasier told me
he'd hired an Englishwoman,

245
00:11:37,247 --> 00:11:40,796
I pictured someone a little more...
Not quite so...

246
00:11:40,967 --> 00:11:42,685
You're Daphne?

247
00:11:42,847 --> 00:11:45,156
- Right again. It's nice to meet you.
- Look at you, Niles.

248
00:11:45,327 --> 00:11:48,444
The woman's a stranger to you and yet
you're ready to hand her your heart.

249
00:11:48,607 --> 00:11:52,361
Well, I may have been a tad smitten.
What's your point?

250
00:11:52,527 --> 00:11:55,883
My point is... Niles, pay attention.

251
00:11:56,367 --> 00:11:58,597
My point is, your so-called
realistic picture of Daphne

252
00:11:58,767 --> 00:12:01,964
has been clouded from the start
by your intense attraction to her.

253
00:12:02,127 --> 00:12:05,802
All right. Perhaps at the beginning
I was blinded by infatuation.

254
00:12:05,967 --> 00:12:08,527
But over the years,
I've learned everything about her.

255
00:12:08,687 --> 00:12:10,359
And my love has only deepened.

256
00:12:10,527 --> 00:12:14,566
I've learned that she's caring
and compassionate. Uh...

257
00:12:14,727 --> 00:12:17,002
And she can be moody sometimes.

258
00:12:17,767 --> 00:12:21,646
She likes jelly on her pancakes
instead of syrup. Uh...

259
00:12:21,847 --> 00:12:24,919
Her laugh, it's like music.

260
00:12:25,087 --> 00:12:27,681
Oh, and that girl can dance.

261
00:12:27,847 --> 00:12:29,565
You're beautiful. You're a goddess.

262
00:12:29,727 --> 00:12:32,241
Oh, I don't ever want
this moment to end.

263
00:12:32,407 --> 00:12:33,396
Then let's not let it.

264
00:12:33,567 --> 00:12:35,285
NILES:
This is one of my favourite memories.

265
00:12:35,447 --> 00:12:37,722
See, that's the dress
I wanted her to wear this weekend.

266
00:12:37,887 --> 00:12:39,605
Isn't she spectacular?

267
00:12:39,767 --> 00:12:41,041
FRASIER:
Indeed she is.

268
00:12:41,207 --> 00:12:44,244
She's perfect.
Oh, wait, look at this. Watch.

269
00:12:46,327 --> 00:12:47,806
[CROWD GASPING]

270
00:12:47,967 --> 00:12:49,480
I come here often.

271
00:12:49,647 --> 00:12:51,956
I suspect a part of you
has never left.

272
00:12:52,127 --> 00:12:53,765
Can you blame me? Look at us.

273
00:12:53,927 --> 00:12:57,317
We're magnificent together.
We're moving in perfect sync.

274
00:12:57,487 --> 00:12:59,284
There's that word perfect again.

275
00:13:00,127 --> 00:13:01,401
I know what you're thinking.

276
00:13:01,567 --> 00:13:04,445
Just because this evening was perfect
doesn't mean I'm idealising Daphne.

277
00:13:04,607 --> 00:13:06,837
Did you hear yourself out there?
You called her a goddess.

278
00:13:07,007 --> 00:13:08,725
You can't build
a higher pedestal than that.

279
00:13:08,887 --> 00:13:11,401
Who could possibly compete
with that sort of image?

280
00:13:13,127 --> 00:13:16,085
That's not fair. I'm well aware
that's just one side of her.

281
00:13:16,247 --> 00:13:20,035
I'm also acquainted with her
ordinary, domestic, everyday side.

282
00:13:20,207 --> 00:13:23,404
[HUMMING]

283
00:13:23,567 --> 00:13:26,957
<i>Heart and soul</i>
<i>I fell in love with you</i>

284
00:13:27,127 --> 00:13:30,403
<i>Heart and soul</i>
<i>The way a fool would do...</i>

285
00:13:30,967 --> 00:13:32,639
- Oh, please.
- What?

286
00:13:32,807 --> 00:13:34,923
Even your everyday memories
are idealised.

287
00:13:35,087 --> 00:13:37,726
How long until the cartoon bluebird
lands on her shoulder?

288
00:13:37,887 --> 00:13:42,403
All right, so maybe my memories
of Daphne are perfect.

289
00:13:42,567 --> 00:13:46,879
Did it ever occur to you
that perhaps Daphne just is perfect?

290
00:13:47,047 --> 00:13:48,685
BOTH:
<i>Because you held me tight</i>

291
00:13:48,847 --> 00:13:50,326
<i>I held you tight.</i>
<i>It serves you right</i>

292
00:13:50,487 --> 00:13:53,240
<i>I stole a kiss in the night</i>

293
00:13:53,407 --> 00:13:54,601
FRASIER:
<i>That's it. I'm going home.</i>

294
00:13:54,767 --> 00:13:56,359
NILES:
Wait, wait, wait. How come?

295
00:13:56,527 --> 00:13:58,483
Nothing else to say.

296
00:13:59,007 --> 00:14:02,079
Niles, I love you.

297
00:14:02,247 --> 00:14:04,363
And I love Daphne.

298
00:14:05,207 --> 00:14:07,562
I just hope the two of you
can work this thing out together.

299
00:14:07,727 --> 00:14:09,877
No, wait, wait, wait.
Don't go, don't go.

300
00:14:10,047 --> 00:14:11,116
Help me understand.

301
00:14:11,287 --> 00:14:13,642
Why is everyone acting
like I've done something wrong?

302
00:14:13,807 --> 00:14:17,880
The only thing I am guilty of is loving
Daphne, and that's all I've ever done.

303
00:14:18,047 --> 00:14:20,641
Yes, yes.
And how did you love her?

304
00:14:20,807 --> 00:14:22,286
From afar.

305
00:14:22,447 --> 00:14:25,757
You were never in love with her.
You were in love at her.

306
00:14:26,287 --> 00:14:30,075
Now you've been given a chance
to experience her in a real relationship,

307
00:14:30,247 --> 00:14:32,636
and yet for some reason
you're resisting it.

308
00:14:32,807 --> 00:14:37,642
Rather than see her as she really is,
you keep holding on to the fantasy.

309
00:14:38,647 --> 00:14:40,285
No, that's not true.

310
00:14:40,447 --> 00:14:44,122
Niles, the woman gained 60 pounds.

311
00:14:44,287 --> 00:14:47,597
And everybody in the world
saw it but you.

312
00:14:47,767 --> 00:14:53,000
All you ever saw
was a perfect woman in a red dress.

313
00:14:57,967 --> 00:14:59,685
Ahem. Okay.

314
00:14:59,847 --> 00:15:05,319
If you're right, and that's a big if,
why would I do that?

315
00:15:05,927 --> 00:15:09,442
Maybe Daphne's not the only one
who's afraid she won't measure up.

316
00:15:09,807 --> 00:15:11,684
Maybe you're afraid too.

317
00:15:12,327 --> 00:15:15,717
After all, if it turns out
that she's not perfect,

318
00:15:16,407 --> 00:15:19,319
then there's a chance
things won't work out.

319
00:15:20,687 --> 00:15:23,679
Then not only
will you lose Daphne,

320
00:15:24,447 --> 00:15:29,567
but you'll have wasted
the last seven years of your life

321
00:15:30,087 --> 00:15:32,043
chasing an illusion.

322
00:15:38,047 --> 00:15:39,639
Oh, Roz, what a pleasant surprise.

323
00:15:39,807 --> 00:15:42,844
Break out the champagne.
I just sold my children's book.

324
00:15:43,007 --> 00:15:45,999
- Hey, that's great.
- Oh, well, congratulations, Roz.

325
00:15:46,167 --> 00:15:48,044
Thanks. This young editor
was like 23 years old.

326
00:15:48,207 --> 00:15:49,322
His name was Scott.

327
00:15:49,487 --> 00:15:52,126
And I figured he'd just be
into action figures and video games,

328
00:15:52,287 --> 00:15:55,359
and there I was with this
simple little story, but he loved it.

329
00:15:55,527 --> 00:15:56,721
FRASIER:
Great. Congratulations.

330
00:15:56,887 --> 00:15:59,242
I've been saving a special bottle
for just such an occasion.

331
00:15:59,407 --> 00:16:02,479
While you're in there,
get me my very special can.

332
00:16:03,327 --> 00:16:04,396
I've gotta call my mother.

333
00:16:04,567 --> 00:16:06,205
She is gonna get
such a kick out of this.

334
00:16:07,087 --> 00:16:09,237
Mom?
Hey, do you remember that story

335
00:16:09,407 --> 00:16:11,045
that you used to tell me
when I was a kid?

336
00:16:11,207 --> 00:16:14,040
You know, about the little girl
and her grandfather?

337
00:16:14,207 --> 00:16:17,279
Yes, well, I just got it published.

338
00:16:17,447 --> 00:16:19,199
[CHUCKLING]

339
00:16:20,327 --> 00:16:21,806
What?

340
00:16:22,887 --> 00:16:24,843
Well, you never told me that.

341
00:16:25,327 --> 00:16:27,841
Okay, fine. Just forget I called.

342
00:16:28,007 --> 00:16:28,996
[CORK POPS]

343
00:16:29,167 --> 00:16:31,283
- Well, you can put that away.
- What happened?

344
00:16:31,447 --> 00:16:34,996
Apparently I just
sold my publisher <i>Heidi.</i>

345
00:16:38,967 --> 00:16:41,356
I better get over there
and let him know before he...

346
00:16:41,527 --> 00:16:42,516
[CELL PHONE RINGS]

347
00:16:42,687 --> 00:16:44,325
Hello. Oh, hey, Scott.

348
00:16:44,487 --> 00:16:46,921
I know, I just heard. Weird, huh?

349
00:16:47,087 --> 00:16:48,998
- Tell him about Eddie.
- Shh.

350
00:16:49,847 --> 00:16:51,565
I am so sorry.

351
00:16:51,727 --> 00:16:54,036
It was a movie too?

352
00:16:55,047 --> 00:16:57,481
NILES: Oh. Hi.
ROZ: Hey.

353
00:16:57,647 --> 00:16:59,239
Hey, Frasier. Hi, Dad. Ahem.

354
00:16:59,407 --> 00:17:00,920
- Hi, Niles.
- Hi, Niles.

355
00:17:01,527 --> 00:17:04,200
- Hello, Daphne.
- Hello.

356
00:17:05,767 --> 00:17:08,964
Dad, what do you say we head out
for dinner over at the steakhouse?

357
00:17:09,127 --> 00:17:11,038
- The steakhouse? Really?
- What the hell.

358
00:17:11,207 --> 00:17:14,517
The blood's just been flying
through my arteries lately.

359
00:17:14,687 --> 00:17:16,518
MARTIN: Give me a minute.
FRASIER: Right.

360
00:17:17,727 --> 00:17:19,319
Daphne,

361
00:17:20,647 --> 00:17:22,444
I want to apologise
for the other night.

362
00:17:22,607 --> 00:17:27,522
I was rude and disrespectful,
and I'm sorry I hurt you.

363
00:17:28,127 --> 00:17:29,321
[SIGHS]

364
00:17:29,487 --> 00:17:31,000
Apology accepted.

365
00:17:31,367 --> 00:17:34,006
- Oh, come here.
- Thank you.

366
00:17:35,767 --> 00:17:37,883
You know, I was just about
to make myself some dinner.

367
00:17:38,047 --> 00:17:39,958
- Would you like to join me?
- I would love that.

368
00:17:40,127 --> 00:17:41,480
Okay.

369
00:17:41,647 --> 00:17:42,841
Actually, wait, Daphne.

370
00:17:44,327 --> 00:17:45,806
I'm gonna pass on dinner.

371
00:17:45,967 --> 00:17:49,243
- Oh, it's no trouble.
- No, I know. It's just that...

372
00:17:49,967 --> 00:17:52,720
I don't really care
for your cooking.

373
00:17:53,087 --> 00:17:54,486
What?

374
00:17:57,087 --> 00:18:01,000
Well, you're not the best cook
in the world.

375
00:18:01,527 --> 00:18:06,203
In fact, you're not very good
at cooking at all.

376
00:18:06,367 --> 00:18:09,086
Bad, bad cook.

377
00:18:10,727 --> 00:18:12,638
- What the hell is he doing?
- Uh...

378
00:18:12,807 --> 00:18:14,320
Well, we're off.

379
00:18:17,367 --> 00:18:19,597
God bless you, son.

380
00:18:27,887 --> 00:18:28,956
You okay?

381
00:18:29,127 --> 00:18:32,563
How could I be after that horrible thing
you just said to me?

382
00:18:32,727 --> 00:18:33,762
Oh, I'm sorry, darling.

383
00:18:33,927 --> 00:18:38,205
I just wanna show you
that I see you the way you really are.

384
00:18:38,807 --> 00:18:41,799
And who I am is a bad cook,
is that what you're saying?

385
00:18:41,967 --> 00:18:46,085
No, no, no, that's not fair.
I thought this was what you wanted.

386
00:18:46,247 --> 00:18:49,239
Well, it still hurts.
I have feelings, you know.

387
00:18:50,007 --> 00:18:52,237
I thought you loved my cooking.

388
00:18:52,407 --> 00:18:54,318
Well, you certainly
could've handled this better.

389
00:18:54,487 --> 00:18:57,047
Well...
Then I don't know what you want.

390
00:18:57,687 --> 00:19:00,679
I can't read minds, you know.
And by the way, neither can you.

391
00:19:02,007 --> 00:19:04,885
Are you saying
you don't think I'm psychic?

392
00:19:05,047 --> 00:19:07,845
Not if you thought
I loved your cooking.

393
00:19:08,847 --> 00:19:12,886
Well, I'm sorry it's not
that hoity-toity crap you eat.

394
00:19:13,327 --> 00:19:16,080
What does that mean?
You think I'm pretentious?

395
00:19:16,247 --> 00:19:19,557
Ho. You'd eat a worm
if I gave it a French name.

396
00:19:21,647 --> 00:19:24,798
Well, fine. If that's the way you feel,
maybe I'll just have dinner by myself.

397
00:19:24,967 --> 00:19:28,403
Well, good. It'll spare you the hell
that's my cooking.

398
00:19:30,767 --> 00:19:33,406
I am so sorry.
I love you so much.

399
00:19:35,727 --> 00:19:37,080
I didn't mean any of those things.

400
00:19:37,247 --> 00:19:40,398
Oh, yes you did. And I did too.

401
00:19:40,567 --> 00:19:43,923
You're a pretentious snob
with your wine and your opera.

402
00:19:44,087 --> 00:19:48,285
Well, you never give
opera a chance!

403
00:19:49,367 --> 00:19:50,959
You're too judgemental.

404
00:19:51,127 --> 00:19:52,845
And you're a clean freak.

405
00:19:53,007 --> 00:19:56,443
Well... I hate your unicorn collection.

406
00:19:56,607 --> 00:19:59,963
And I hate that your closet
is bigger than mine.

407
00:20:00,127 --> 00:20:03,324
Well... you're too tall.

408
00:20:04,167 --> 00:20:06,556
- You're too short.
- Well...

409
00:20:07,087 --> 00:20:10,159
[BOTH MOANING]

410
00:20:11,447 --> 00:20:13,119
Oh, Daphne.

411
00:20:13,287 --> 00:20:15,403
Oh, Niles.

412
00:20:20,727 --> 00:20:24,242
Ah. There you are, Niles.
May I have a latte, please?

413
00:20:24,407 --> 00:20:27,444
So how are things
with you and Daphne, hmm?

414
00:20:32,327 --> 00:20:34,443
Oh. Thank you.

415
00:20:37,807 --> 00:20:39,525
Niles, is everything okay?

416
00:20:45,567 --> 00:20:46,682
Ah.

417
00:20:51,327 --> 00:20:53,363
You know the best part, Frasier?

418
00:20:54,447 --> 00:20:57,120
It wasn't at all like I imagined it.

419
00:21:08,207 --> 00:21:09,276
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

